  "prompt": "What is XS3 code?",
  "response": "XS3 code, also known as Excess-3 code or XS-3 code, is a non-weighted code used to express decimal numbers. It is a type of binary-coded decimal (BCD) code that represents each decimal digit by its corresponding 4-bit binary equivalent, but with an offset of 3. This means that to convert a decimal digit to XS3 code, you take the binary representation of the digit and add 3 to it.\n\nFor example, the decimal digit '0' is represented as '0000' in binary. In XS3 code, you would add 3 to this digit:\n\n- Decimal 0: 0 + 3 = 3 \u2192 Binary 0011\n- Decimal 1: 1 + 3 = 4 \u2192 Binary 0100\n- Decimal 2: 2 + 3 = 5 \u2192 Binary 0101\n- Decimal 3: 3 + 3 = 6 \u2192 Binary 0110\n- Decimal 4: 4 + 3 = 7 \u2192 Binary 0111\n- Decimal 5: 5 + 3 = 8 \u2192 Binary 1000\n- Decimal 6: 6 + 3 = 9 \u2192 Binary 1001\n- Decimal 7: 7 + 3 = 10 \u2192 Binary 1010\n- Decimal 8: 8 + 3 = 11 \u2192 Binary 1011\n- Decimal 9: 9 + 3 = 12 \u2192 Binary 1100\n\nThe XS3 code is useful in digital systems, particularly in applications involving electronic displays, since it facilitates error detection and is easier to manage in some arithmetic operations compared to standard binary coding.",
